reconciliation: “Aemilius quoque Lepidus et Fulvius Flaccus, nobili genere amplissi- misque honoribus et summo loco in civitate praediti, odio inter sese gravi et simultate diutina conflictati sunt. Postea populus eos simul censores facit ; atque illi ubi voce praeconis renuntiati sunt, ibidem in campo statim nondum dimissa contione ultro uter- que et pari voluntate conjuncti complexique sunt3 exque eo die et in ipsa censura et postea jugi concordia fidissime amplissime- que vixerunt.” Abrami has a good note on this Lepidus. He is supposed to be the Lepidus who killed an enemy in battle, and at the same time saved a citizen’s life when he was a boy of fifteen. Lepidus annorum xv praetextatus hostem occidit civem servavit.'’ Lepidus was consul B.c. 187, 175, and he was elected Pontifex Maximus in B.c. 180. The year of his censorship was B.c. 179. The direc- tions which he gave for his simple funeral (Liv. Ep. 48) shew that he was one of the Romans of the better sort.
